text: Footnote: I come from a family of afro-american vets, and great-gran-daddy fought the Nazis in World War II in an all  black segregated unit. So i'm a big military history guy and i've been with my family to alot of veterans associations and parades, etc. (before a dumbass makes a racist comment about blacks despite them fighting for the country kicking ass in many wars up through today)  Now. With that said: *WHY IS THIS AN INTEGRATED UNIT IN WORLD WAR II?!?!?* LOL. This isn't debateable, there's no other 'opinions'. "It's 100% flat historical fact that the military was de facto segregated*. Hollywood isn't dumb enough not to know this as they've made dozens of World War II movies for decades including those that ACKNOWLEDGE THIS LOL. I just don't get why the hell they couldn't even bother with this fact just out of desperation to have a 'black protagonist'. They could've easily done this and had two units stranded in one location, one black one white--which would've made a good paranoia scenario once you throw zombies in the mix--thus gotten what you wnated, had a black soldier character shooting guns, explosions, CGI, FX, gore, etc lol everything that they had in this trailer. Don't get me wrong, despite that this is obviously a rip off of Frankenstein's Monsters, Wolfenstein and Call of Duty: Zombies DLC I still love to be entertained by this movie. The concept is fun and looks badass. I just hate how they totally fucked up with THAT historical accuracy which was so in your face and OBVIOUS during the 40's!  I mean is there an explanation for why the guy is even flying in with other soldiers? It's not even acknowledged ore explained lol. It's just "oh hey....time to go on a special mission". I'm of the school where I hate hyper-PC crap, I feel having a genuinely written story and role for minority characters is better than ignoring history just to shoe-horn someone in to be a Token. But Hollywood is too damn politically correct to do that, since that would require *originality*.

text: Now, originally, this film was to be set within the Cloverfield (multi)verse, but I believe after the backlash of the Cloverfield Paradox, J.J. Abrams decided to cut the ties it originally had with that film universe. I heard that he stated at a convention that this film was not officially a part of the "Clover-verse" (personally taking that with a grain of salt, because he has lied to try to keep the surprise in an upcoming film) but, I personally did not hate the Cloverfield Paradox. I thought the movie was pretty entertaining as far as sci-fi thrillers go, and added more lore to the world he had been building. I hope this does end up having at least a small time to the Cloverfield films, but even if it isn't, I'll still be going to see it!

OVERLORD noun a person who is lord over another or over other lords: to obey the will of one's sovereign and overlord. a person of great influence, authority, power, or the like: the overlords of industry.  So yeah, I have a hard time understanding how this word applies to a nazi zombie factory, unless it is for some dumb reason like that this nazi project is called project Overlord or something(which still does not make sense, calling it project Lazarus would make sense). I wanna thank Activision, EPIC(Fortnite), Blizzard, Zipper Interactive(SoCoM), Hollywood in general, and all the little fuckboys who support them and their continued support of Lootboxes/Crates, useless purchasable weapon skins, useless purchasable character skins, pay-to-win bullshit.  And I don't know how but this is also your fault EA, Hello Games, Microsoft, your greedy lying executives, and public relations managers.  To be honest I thought it was going to be an inspiring tale of overcoming adversity, the sheer courage of the men and women who fought in the war, and contributed to the war effort to fight for a worthy cause, like Saving Private Rayan, FURY, Unbroken, Hacksaw Ridge, ext.  But sadly no, as soon as I saw the red "Serum" I knew this was another attempt to catch the attention of the new gen kids, who still haven't out grown diapers by the way but apparently have all slept with my mother, and videogame fuckboys who'd gladly pay $60 for a skin pack that includes an in-game T-shirt for their character that looks like its covered in Tide Pods and Emojis, a slightly shiny butter knife, and a phone mount up their arse, lifted onto a hoverboard if it made them look slightly trendy, and edgy, and you could make it clickbaitable on Social Media. text: I'm so sick of the hypocrisy of the SJWs in Hollywood. I looked this up to be sure and the military wasn't integrated during the Normandy invasion. They just stuck a black guy in that role cause muh diversity....  Why not stick a few black guys on the German side too. And while your at it throw in a few female front line combat troops because wahman power.  Imagine for one second the outrage that would happen if they made a movie based in Africa like (Zulu, Shaka Zulu or Black Panther, etc), but the lead character(and only a few others) was white... in Africa... killing black people... and all the bad guys are black...  For fucks sake at least structure the plot where it makes sense. Have him be a Tuskegee Airman that gets shot down or SOMETHING. Although they didn't participate in Operation overlord.  Hollywood loves remakes. Let's remake Tuskegee Airman with the lead character being a white guy(the only one in the whole squadron) that gets all the kills and girls... because diversity is our strength. Even better let's make him a Latino trans man cause yeah gender isn't a thing anymore so why would it be back in the 1940's either.  No, you lunatics just don't care. You want everyone to know him being black is special just because what? Black people are better than white people? Diversity is our strength? You're the worst sort of racist. Because you think your racism is a good thing.  You know what I hate most... You cramming diversity down my throat over and over and over and OVER again makes me notice it and brings out the worst side in me. I shouldn't even notice it. I certainly  shouldn't have to defend my race... because you shouldn't be attacking it.  Don't get me wrong. I respect the black soldiers and airman that did serve in WWII a lot. 700 of them died. I don't have a problem with black lead actors either. I just watch Equalizer 2. Great movie. I'm just sick and tired of Hollywood rewriting history(or worse re-writing established sci-fi or comic book plots/characters) purely for the sake of shoving down everyone's throat that they are a bunch of SJW, virtue signaling, racist, fuck-tards.  I'm over it. Fuck Hollywood.  It's okay to be a strait white male.

text: I know the plot is bullshit, but I‚Äôm kinda pissed off at the construction of the MC. A black draftee in the 101st?  Two major problems there...  1: In WW2 the US Army was still heavily segregated, the 101st was considered an elite unit and they wouldn‚Äôt of let a back person in. To me this spits in the face of everyone who worked to integrate the military by simply ignoring a problem they had to work hard and long to fix.  2: The real kicker though is he‚Äôs a draftee in the 101st?! Paratroopers had to be ‚Äúdouble volunteers‚Äù (as they had to volunteer to enlist, then volunteer to be a paratrooper). That‚Äôs sir, is horseshit!  So while I‚Äôm not going to outright not watch this movie, I am going to ask for a real fucking believable background for this character to exist as he is.

text: The movie that this previews actually DOES look cool, just to make that part very clear from the start. But with the surge in popularity and the ridiculous ease of use google offers, there's NO WAY IN HELL the asshats responsible for the movie didn't know 100% that their title was "coincidentally" the very same title as a very popular Manga/Anime currently in production. And don't for a minute expect us to believe that nobody actually checks when deciding a movie title.  The last time a movie so blatantly took a title that was obviously already in popular use from a manga/anime, we got Avatar from James Cameron, which again was a pretty good movie (I'm not as enthralled as most people seemed to be) but still the title was quite clearly taken on purpose to draw attention it might not otherwise have had...

text: Ah! Alright, my nerd rage movie junkie 2 cents in 3, 2, 1, I fuckin love zombies. As a plot device and literary/cinematic tool and as a character and representation and as a monster. They say monsters are a commentary on how man views itself. It's like a projection of his/her fears.  The concept of zombie combined with the grunt work of soldier and military is GENIUS!! The concept of being mindless, taking orders, being primal...being....expendable üò¢ So many forgotten names... Missions buried. The push for military technology so perverse that it even dabbles in black magic, ancient text and the unthinkable. Anything to win. The mindset of warfare...but...at What cost?  How much war until there is nothing left and we already lost what we were fighting for in the first place. Our humanity.

text: NO Black paratroopers at D-Day or EVER in WW2 (And NO black officers like the jumpmaster over white troops in any unit anywhere under any circumstances EVER during the whole war).  Sorry but true.  US Army was completely segregated at that time. Period. Full Stop. So ANY depiction of black paratroopers of infantry assaulting the beaches at Normandy is just "feelz gud" PC nonsense. Eventually in late 44 there were all black TD (Tank Destroyer) battalions and I think a couple of artillery battalions and maybe (?) a combat engineer regiment, ALL black EXCEPT the officers who were white. That's it for combat arms on the ground. The Army wasn't integrated until AFTER the Korean War, in the mid-late fifties. During the Korean War there were black infantry units. They were officered by whites and were poorly led and equipped. This led to disastrous consequences in battle. The units had very poor morale as they were horribly treated. The result were several instances where the units disentigrated when attacked and they were routed. A board of inquiry exonerated the troops and several white officers were cashiered from service. After Korea, President Eisenhower ordered the integration of ALL branches of service.

text: The only African-American paratrooper unit was indeed the 555th Parachute Infantry Battalion as you have said. This unit was selected via volunteers; these volunteers were members of the 92nd (Buffalo Soldiers) Infantry Division, the famous African-American division still in training at the time at Camp Huachuca, Arizona. This battalion did not serve as combat paratroopers, but instead fought the Japanese in a different way. The Japanese were sending thousands of balloon bombs towards the U.S. Northwest. The 555th's job was to fight the fires that resulted from these bombs.

text: Another experiment going...w r o n g ? You want Horror? Real Horror? I'll give you Horror...  1. Alfred Hitchcock's " PSYCHO " 2. William Friedkin's " THE EXORCIST " 3. Richard Donner's " THE OMEN " 4. George A. Romero's " DAWN OF THE DEAD " 5. Ridley Scott's " A  L  I  E  N " 6. Stanley Kubrick's " THE  SHINING " 7. Tobe Hooper's " THE  FUNHOUSE " 8. John Landis' "AN  AMERICAN WEREWOLF IN LONDON" 9. Tobe Hooper's " POLTERGEIST " 10. David Cronenberg's " THE  FLY "  And the other titles who didn't made it to my top ten list (yet), but were also quite impressive are: " JEEPERS  CREEPERS ",  " DRAG ME TO HELL "  and  " CABIN  IN THE  WOODS ".  Okay,  " THE TEXAS CHAINSAW MASSACRE " (the original!), " SUSPIRIA " (the original!), " HALLOWEEN " (the original!), " THE  ENTITY ", " THE  AMITYVILLE  HORROR ", " SCREAM ", " I KNOW WHAT YOU DID LAST SUMMER " , " SLEEPY HOLLOW " and " WORLD WAR Z " weren't that bad either. But only time will tell which film will be hailed as: The...S c a r i e s t... HorrorFilm...E v e r ... And no, it isn't going to be " WEEKEND AT BERNIE'S ". text: There's always this tendency for supernatural movies with a historical setting, or any setting that many people take seriously, that will always end up in disaster. Not many people can pull that kind of thing off.    In my complete, unbiased opinion, Overlord does an exceptional job at putting together supernatural elements in the historical setting. It's strange to think about it. You know this isn't non-fictional, and you know it couldn't have happened, yet it feels so much like a classic WW2 movie..   There is a nice balance between the main characters coming into conflict with both the infected zombies and human German soldiers, which adds for a very nice mixture. Like rum and coke :)   If you're looking for the more charming aspect of WW2, then you won't be disappointed. The film fits the setting very well. For example, there is one scene where an Allied soldier is using an MG-42, and his friend next to him tells him to hurry up when he reloads. The soldier using the machine gun then responds unpleasantly, "It's a two person gun you idiot!" I know it isn't a huge example, but the fact of the matter still stands. There is accurate usage of weaponry for the most part with excellent sound design.     I would give it a solid 8/10 which is surprising for a movie that is literally nicknamed "Nazi Zombies"

text: Okay I just saw this movie in theaters and well I am disappointed to say the least. It does not look like a cheaply made film and the special effects are done well but at certain points you have to suspend your disbelief, and that doesn‚Äôt even involve the Nazi super serum.   For example there is a part in the movie where they are hiding in a house and they have to keep quiet because the Germans are patrolling the town. They capture one of the officers but they don‚Äôt ever gag him and you have to believe this soldier would not scream for help. And yes he could just be trying to stay alive because the Americans would kill him if he screamed but this is a member of the Waffen SS, they‚Äôre the elite of the German Army.  Another comes when they get to torturing this officer for information, the dude still doesn‚Äôt scream for help but in the process of torturing him they appear to make a lot of noise. Now I don‚Äôt know how old French houses are built, maybe they are soundproof with no door closing off the place they are torturing the officer at from the rest of the house but it begins to kill the idea if they have to be quiet.  It is a beautiful film to look at with some okay actors and and meh plot. Get whoever did these special effects and put them in charge of more films.

text: Just saw this flick and it's really well made.  The scenes at the beginning when the commando team has to fly into German occupied France to blow up a radio tower are top notch.  Along the way the soldiers discover a secret Nazi lab in the basement of the building with the tower, which was an abandoned church, in which a German scientist is trying to create super soldiers for the Third Reich by reanimating the corpses of dead soldiers.  They do have a serum that does that, but it turns the reanimated soldiers into homicidal maniacs who cannot be controlled.   To make matters worst, the reanimated soldiers have enhanced regeneration ability so killing them with knives and bullets is very difficult.  However, flame throwers are more effect! If someone is a fan of zombie and war films, they will find this one worth viewing, imo.

text: Isn't it funny the Allied troops promoted segregation and rank limitations, During World War II, African-American enlistment was at an all-time high, with more than 1 million serving in the armed forces.[8] However, the U.S. military was still heavily segregated.The marines had no blacks enlisted in their ranks. There were blacks in the Navy Seabees and the United States Air Force (Tuskegee Airmen). The army had only five African-American officers.[8] In addition, no African-American would receive the Medal of Honor during the war, and their tasks in the war were largely reserved to noncombat units. Black soldiers had to sometimes give up their seats in trains to the Nazi prisoners of war...

Even as a WWII admirer, I do like it when some fictional sci-fi, or horror stuff is added. Sometimes it‚Äôs best to see something new for a change. I would love to see it again in the future. text: Think this is a good movie (good plot, acting, and general production) but feel its also unnecessarily ruined by being too blatantly PC. Its not a train-smash but I think its sad that the such a well made movie is "diminished" for such a reason. I've resigned myself to expect a bit of PC in every movie (and series) that comes out these days, though it would be nice if they could be a bit more subtle (and realistic) about it.    The argument that "its just a zombie/fantasy movie, so who cares?" is really not good enough here. The basic purpose of any fantasy movie is to "immerse" the audience in the fantasy world and make it "believable" up to point where you don't really notice the "fantasy/falsehood", ie. you're "sucked in". So, obviously zombies are fantasy creatures but "unrealistic zombies" are also immersion-breaking. In this case, the zombies were done well, however, making movies (or series, or anything) based in historical times (whether it includes a fantasy element of zombies, robot dinosaurs, or rainbow unicorns, etc), where a general standard of realism is upheld EXCEPT when it comes to racism and racial segregation, which, for some weird unexplained reason, doesn't exist, or is ignored, or altered into contrived unrealistic scenarios, is also just really strange and immersion-breaking.   Because its "noticeable" (and in my opinion "suspicious"), and it instantly pops the spell-binding bubble of fantasy that movie had been weaving up till then. In this movie its right from he beginning. Its not that I didn't like Adepo's (and Woodbine's) performances. I thought they were great. Within the story I just thought their positions and relationships with the other soldiers "within the context of the era in which it was set" was noticeably contrived, and it set an unnecessary "unrealistic tone" to the movie right from the start.  I just feel its all silly and unnecessary, and its kind of ruining  movies (and series) in general these days.

Was just the practices of the times, honestly. But hey, it's a movie about nazi fuckin' zombies, so it's not like we're shooting for the historical accuracy of storming the beaches of Normandy here. text: OVER LORD ALERT SPEAKER PALOSI FLINT COMMON WEALTH CA ALERT     Science Bottled Water With High Arsenic Levels Sold At Target, Whole Foods, Walmart By Denise Nellasca  06/21/19 AT 5:56 AM 00:39 Flint Water Crisis: The Fallout Four Years Later People don‚Äôt usually think twice about buying bottled water. Feeling thirsty while you‚Äôre out? Just head to a nearby shop and buy some bottled water. In addition to being an easily accessible form of hydration, it‚Äôs also believed that bottled water is safer and healthier to drink compared to tap water. However, a recent study says otherwise.     USA TODAY Money ‚úî @USATODAYmoney  A test conducted by an Oakland nonprofit finds Pe√±afiel and Starkey bottled water contain levels of arsenic that violate state guidelines. http://rssfeeds.usatoday.com/~/603323836/0/usatodaycommoney-topstories~High-levels-of-arsenic-in-bottled-water-sold-at-Whole-Foods-Target-Walmart-study-says/ ‚Ä¶   7 4:37 PM - Jun 20, 2019 Twitter Ads info and privacy   High levels of arsenic in bottled water sold at Whole Foods, Target, Walmart, study says A test conducted by an Oakland nonprofit finds Pe√±afiel and Starkey bottled water contain levels of arsenic that violate state guidelines.   usatoday.com See USA TODAY Money's other Tweets Bottled water is purchased at extremely high rates, especially in places like Flint, Michigan where there is currently a water crisis and people have no choice but to turn to bottled water for clean water. However, bottled water may not be as safe as you think. A test conducted by the California nonprofit Center for Environmental Health found that two bottled water brands‚ÄîStarkey, owned by Whole Foods and Pe√±afiel, owned by Keurig Dr. Pepper‚Äîcontained levels of arsenic higher than tap water. The level of arsenic is so high that this violates state guidelines.       California law states that high levels of arsenic can cause cancer and reproductive harm. Therefore, products that violate the recommended state levels of arsenic need to be labeled with a warning.   ‚ÄúCustomers typically purchase bottled water at exorbitantly high costs with the assumption that it is safer and healthier to drink than tap water, unaware that they are ingesting an extremely toxic metal linked to birth defects and cancer,‚Äù Michael Green, the organization‚Äôs CEO, said in a statement.   Studies also show that high levels of arsenic can cause organ damage and hormone disruption, especially in children as their bodies are still developing.   According to the study: ‚ÄúDirect exposure can affect mental and physical development [‚Ä¶] Arsenic can even harm an unborn child as a result of exposure to pregnant women or women likely to become pregnant. Arsenic in drinking water can cause an increased risk of heart disease, including high blood pressure and diabetes. The metal is also what is known as an ‚Äòendocrine disrupting chemical,‚Äô which means even small doses can wreak havoc on a human‚Äôs hormone system.‚Äù   This study corroborates independent findings released earlier this year by Consumer Reports. The findings stated that the same brands of bottled water had nearly double the federal limit of arsenic levels in their water.

text: Just a quick critical review and i know im late to review it. Before i watched this movie at a discount theatre i have not heard of this movie. I didnt watch any trailers prior to seeing it but judging by the title i assumed it was about ww2. When the movie started it was a full on ww2 experience. The planes, flack, the static line jump, and the normandy landing was grade A ww2 filmmaking. And i didnt discover the twist from ww2 to fiction until the "van helsing village scene." I think we all secretly wanted a nazi zombies movie and i wasnt dissapointed. Overall a 9/10 movie. Now the only thing (i know people have said it dosent matter) was the black soldier. I 100% agree, It really dosent matter since it is fiction. However, my initial reaction to the ww2 setting in the beginning was outstanding and when the camera showed a black dude in a stick of all white dudes my reaction was like more than confused and i think this is because i was expecting an immersive ww2 film judging from the first opening scene, but the main issue is that i also  thought this film was going to break that trend in todays media on forced diversity since it was going to be about ww2. Obviously i knew right away it was fiction after the opening scene so i didnt care if the dude was black. Diversity is good and should be an important part in any movie but you can tell that if they didnt include at least one diverse character then it would be considered "racist." I loved the movie but, feel free to disagree with me, i believe that forced diversity, political agendas, or political stances needs to be removed or banned from all entertainment. There are many examples of forced diversity in a lot of movies and video games and this needs to stop.
